      Bank hearings
   =20
 =20

We   talked the other day about the mechanics of Silicon Valley Bank=E2=80=
=99s failure. Those mechanics are that a lot of depositors asked for their =
money back one Thursday, and SVB didn=E2=80=99t have enough money to give t=
hem: It ended the day with negative money, and was shut down by its regulat=
ors. This is a somewhat weird thing to happen in a modern banking system: S=
ilicon Valley Bank had lots of valuable, safe, liquid=C2=A0assets, and it i=
s a US bank with access to the Federal Reserve. It seems like it should hav=
e been fairly straightforward for SVB to pledge those assets to the Federal=
 Reserve to borrow enough money to meet its deposit outflows.
And in fact SVB tried to do that, and it apparently did have enough collate=
ral to borrow enough money to pay out its depositors that Thursday, though =
I=E2=80=99m not sure it would have survived the weekend. But the problem, t=
hat Thursday, was not that SVB had insufficient assets; the problem was tha=
t the Fed=E2=80=99s computer systems stopped working at 4 p.m. California t=
ime, and SVB missed the cutoff to transfer assets and borrow money. Silicon=
 Valley Bank certainly had financial problems =E2=80=94=C2=A0the Federal De=
posit Insurance Corp. finally   sold it off yesterday for something like ne=
gative $20 billion!
  [1]
=C2=A0=E2=80=94 but the reason it failed=C2=A0that day=C2=A0was mostly oper=
ational, not financial.
Today the US Senate is  holding a hearing on =E2=80=9CRecent Bank Failures =
and the Federal Regulatory Response.=E2=80=9D Here are the prepared testimo=
nies of  Michael Barr, the vice chair for supervision at the Federal Reserv=
e, Martin Gruenberg, the chairman of the FDIC, and  Nellie Liang, the under=
secretary for domestic finance at the US Treasury.
Gruenberg=E2=80=99s testimony helps clear up one small mystery of the recen=
t bank failures: What happened to Signature Bank of New York? Signature was=
 taken over by the FDIC the same weekend that SVB was, and while SVB had cl=
early run out of money, it was less clear that Signature had. Signature boa=
rd member (and former congressman, author of the Dodd-Frank Act, etc.)=20
Barney Frank complained that Signature was actually doing fine, that its ou=
tflows had stabilized, and that =E2=80=9Cif we=E2=80=99d been allowed to op=
en tomorrow, that we could=E2=80=99ve continued.=E2=80=9D But its   state r=
egulator said that it had had =E2=80=9Ca significant crisis of confidence i=
n the bank=E2=80=99s leadership,=E2=80=9D and shut it. Since Signature was =
one of the main banks for the crypto industry, this led to theories that th=
e takeover of Signature was part of a regulatory crackdown on crypto rather=
 than an actual bank failure.
But here is Gruenberg today:

Subsequently, as word of SVB=E2=80=99s problems began to spread, Signature =
Bank began to experience contagion effects with deposit outflows that began=
 on March 9 and became acute on Friday, March 10, with the announcement of =
SVB=E2=80=99s failure. On March 10, Signature Bank lost=C2=A020 percent of =
its total deposits in a matter of hours, depleting its cash position and le=
aving it with a negative balance with the Federal Reserve as of close of bu=
siness. Bank management could not provide accurate data regarding the amoun=
t of the deficit, and resolution of the negative balance required a prolong=
ed joint effort among Signature Bank, regulators, and the Federal Home Loan=
 Bank of New York to pledge collateral and obtain the necessary funding fro=
m the Federal Reserve=E2=80=99s Discount Window to cover the negative outfl=
ows. This was accomplished with minutes to spare before the Federal Reserve=
=E2=80=99s wire room closed.
Over the weekend, liquidity risk at the bank rose to a critical level as wi=
thdrawal requests mounted, along with uncertainties about meeting those req=
uests, and potentially others in light of the high level of uninsured depos=
its, raised doubts about the bank=E2=80=99s continued viability.

Notice the difference from SVB. On Thursday, SVB tried to move collateral t=
o the Fed to borrow money, but missed the deadline by a few minutes and was=
 shut down the next day. On Friday, Signature tried to move collateral to t=
he Fed to borrow money, and=C2=A0made=C2=A0the cutoff by a few minutes. It =
was shut down over the weekend anyway, for its own operational problems: =
=E2=80=9CBank management could not provide accurate data regarding the amou=
nt of the deficit.=E2=80=9D The problem at SVB is that it ran out of money.=
 The problem at Signature is that it=C2=A0couldn=E2=80=99t figure out how m=
uch money it had. I suspect that this is a more common problem at banks tha=
n would be ideal, but in any case I guess it=E2=80=99s a good enough reason=
 for the regulators to shut a bank down. If you are a bank and you come to =
the Fed on a Friday afternoon and say =E2=80=9Chey, we are out of money, we=
 need more, and we=E2=80=99re not sure how much money we have or need, can =
you help us figure it out,=E2=80=9D apparently the Fed (1) will help you fi=
gure it out and (2) will lend you the money, but you are not opening on Mon=
day.
Meanwhile, the=C2=A0financial=C2=A0story of the failure of SVB=20
is quite straightforward: It had a lot of zero-interest deposits that it in=
vested in long-term loans and (especially) Treasury and agency bonds, and t=
hen the Fed raised interest rates rapidly, those loans and bonds lost value=
, and those zero-interest deposits started looking less stable. Then SVB so=
ld some bonds at a loss and tried to raise capital, which sparked panic amo=
ng its interconnected network of venture capitalist and startup depositors;=
 they all took their money out and SVB went bust.
The hearing today is intended to help figure out the right regulatory respo=
nse to keep this from happening again, but in some sense the takeaway is re=
ally =E2=80=9Cthe traditional business of banking is very risky when the Fe=
d raises interest rates a lot for the first time in ages.=E2=80=9D People g=
ot used to low rates, and then rates rapidly became high, and they were cau=
ght out.=C2=A0Here=E2=80=99s this:

Billionaire Andre Esteves, the co-founder and chairman of Brazil=E2=80=99s =
Banco BTG Pactual SA, said that =E2=80=9Cany junior analyst=E2=80=9D from L=
atin America would have known how to manage the interest rate risk on Silic=
on Valley Bank=E2=80=99s balance sheet to avoid its collapse.=C2=A0
Esteves, speaking at a BTG event in Santiago, Chile, said the volatility ro=
iling global markets is a result of 15 years of complacency during near-zer=
o interest rates that led to widespread excesses. People were caught off gu=
ard when rates suddenly spiked and didn=E2=80=99t have the real life experi=
ence on how to manage those risks, he said.

His point here is not =E2=80=9CSVB were morons and Latin American interns a=
re smart=E2=80=9D; his point here is =E2=80=9CSVB had 15 years of low and s=
table interest rates and Latin American interns did not.=E2=80=9D If you ne=
ver encounter interest rate risk, you might forget how to manage it.
The nice thing about this diagnosis is that it is sort of self-resolving. N=
o bank=C2=A0today is going around taking deposits at 0% and using them to b=
uy mortgage-backed securities at 2%, not because they have learned risk man=
agement lessons from SVB but because interest rates are already higher. The=
 problems at SVB were not about some weird new form of bank risk-taking; th=
