StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
Barney Frank complained</a> that Signature was actually doing fine, that it=
s outflows had stabilized, and that =E2=80=9Cif we=E2=80=99d been allowed t=
o open tomorrow, that we could=E2=80=99ve continued.=E2=80=9D But its <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30986595.262435/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTQvc3ZiLXRvb2=
stdGhlLXdyb25nLXJpc2tzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09Z=
W1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDMyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249=
bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB232e57fd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  state regulator=
 said</a> that it had had =E2=80=9Ca significant crisis of confidence in th=
e bank=E2=80=99s leadership,=E2=80=9D and shut it. Since Signature was one =
of the main banks for the crypto industry, this led to theories that the ta=
keover of Signature was part of a regulatory crackdown on crypto rather tha=
n an actual bank failure.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But here is Gruenberg today:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Subsequently, as word of SVB=E2=80=99s problem=
s began to spread, Signature Bank began to experience contagion effects wit=
h deposit outflows that began on March 9 and became acute on Friday, March =
10, with the announcement of SVB=E2=80=99s failure. On March 10, Signature =
Bank lost=C2=A020 percent of its total deposits in a matter of hours, deple=
ting its cash position and leaving it with a negative balance with the Fede=
ral Reserve as of close of business. Bank management could not provide accu=
rate data regarding the amount of the deficit, and resolution of the negati=
ve balance required a prolonged joint effort among Signature Bank, regulato=
rs, and the Federal Home Loan Bank of New York to pledge collateral and obt=
ain the necessary funding from the Federal Reserve=E2=80=99s Discount Windo=
w to cover the negative outflows. This was accomplished with minutes to spa=
re before the Federal Reserve=E2=80=99s wire room closed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over the weekend, liquidity risk at the bank r=
ose to a critical level as withdrawal requests mounted, along with uncertai=
nties about meeting those requests, and potentially others in light of the =
high level of uninsured deposits, raised doubts about the bank=E2=80=99s co=
ntinued viability.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Notice the difference from SVB. On Thursday, S=
VB tried to move collateral to the Fed to borrow money, but missed the dead=
line by a few minutes and was shut down the next day. On Friday, Signature =
tried to move collateral to the Fed to borrow money, and=C2=A0<em>made=C2=
=A0</em>the cutoff by a few minutes. It was shut down over the weekend anyw=
ay, for its own operational problems: =E2=80=9CBank management could not pr=
ovide accurate data regarding the amount of the deficit.=E2=80=9D The probl=
em at SVB is that it ran out of money. The problem at Signature is that it=
=C2=A0<em>couldn=E2=80=99t figure out how much money it had</em>. I suspect=
 that this is a more common problem at banks than would be ideal, but in an=
y case I guess it=E2=80=99s a good enough reason for the regulators to shut=
 a bank down. If you are a bank and you come to the Fed on a Friday afterno=
on and say =E2=80=9Chey, we are out of money, we need more, and we=E2=80=99=
re not sure how much money we have or need, can you help us figure it out,=
=E2=80=9D apparently the Fed (1) will help you figure it out and (2) will l=
end you the money, but you are not opening on Monday.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, the=C2=A0<em>financial=C2=A0</em>st=
ory of the failure of SVB <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/30986595.262435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTAvc3RhcnR1cC1iYW5rLWhhZC1hLXN0YXJ0dXAtYmFuay1ydW4_Y21waW=
Q9QkJEMDMyODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZ=
XR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzI4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB7970da3d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">
is quite straightforward</a>: It had a lot of zero-interest deposits that i=
t invested in long-term loans and (especially) Treasury and agency bonds, a=
nd then the Fed raised interest rates rapidly, those loans and bonds lost v=
alue, and those zero-interest deposits started looking less stable. Then SV=
B sold some bonds at a loss and tried to raise capital, which sparked panic=
 among its interconnected network of venture capitalist and startup deposit=
ors; they all took their money out and SVB went bust.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The hearing today is intended to help figure o=
ut the right regulatory response to keep this from happening again, but in =
some sense the takeaway is really =E2=80=9Cthe traditional business of bank=
ing is very risky when the Fed raises interest rates a lot for the first ti=
me in ages.=E2=80=9D People got used to low rates, and then rates rapidly b=
ecame high, and they were caught out.=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/30986595.262435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjgvYmlsbGlvbmFpcmUtZXN0ZXZlcy1zYXlzLWFueS1pb=
nRlcm4td291bGQtaGF2ZS1zZWVuLXN2Yi1yaXNrP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZG=
JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDMyOCZ=
1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB07f57ba6" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
Here=E2=80=99s this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Billionaire Andre Esteves, the co-founder and =
chairman of Brazil=E2=80=99s Banco BTG Pactual SA, said that =E2=80=9Cany j=
unior analyst=E2=80=9D from Latin America would have known how to manage th=
e interest rate risk on Silicon Valley Bank=E2=80=99s balance sheet to avoi=
d its collapse.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Esteves, speaking at a BTG event in Santiago, =
Chile, said the volatility roiling global markets is a result of 15 years o=
f complacency during near-zero interest rates that led to widespread excess=
es. People were caught off guard when rates suddenly spiked and didn=E2=80=
=99t have the real life experience on how to manage those risks, he said.</=
p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">His point here is not =E2=80=9CSVB were morons=
 and Latin American interns are smart=E2=80=9D; his point here is =E2=80=9C=
SVB had 15 years of low and stable interest rates and Latin American intern=
s did not.=E2=80=9D If you never encounter interest rate risk, you might fo=
rget how to manage it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The nice thing about this diagnosis is that it=
 is sort of self-resolving. No bank=C2=A0<em>today </em>is going around tak=
ing deposits at 0% and using them to buy mortgage-backed securities at 2%, =
not because they have learned risk management lessons from SVB but because =
interest rates are already higher. The problems at SVB were not about some =
weird new form of bank risk-taking; they were about the traditional busines=
s of banking being fragile in a sudden transition from low rates to high ra=
tes. The solution is to sort of muddle along without bankrupting too many b=
anks until they have all made that transition. And so the Fed=E2=80=99s mai=
n response to SVB was to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/30986595.262435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTMvc3ZiLWNvdWxkbi10LWlnbm9yZS1pdHMtbG9zc2VzLWJ1dC10aGUtZmV=
kLWNhbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzI4MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3=
VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCe6bf97ce" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  create a new funding program</a=
> that will let banks continue to ignore their interest-rate losses for one=
 more year: You give the banks another year to muddle through, and figure t=
hat whoever successfully muddles through that year will be fine.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still you can=E2=80=99t go to Congress and be =
like =E2=80=9Cyeah raising rates blew up some banks, whaddarya gonna do.=E2=
=80=9D So <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30986595=
.262435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjg=
vdXMtb2ZmaWNpYWxzLXNpZ25hbC1uZXctcnVsZXMtbG9vbS1hZnRlci1zdmItc2lnbmF0dXJlLW=
ZhaWx1cmVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjgyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX=
3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDMyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVm=
Zg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBda6584de" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  there will be new rules</a>=
:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Top US financial officials on Tuesday outlined=
 what=E2=80=99s likely to be the biggest regulatory overhaul of the banking=
 sector in years, in an initiative aimed at addressing underlying issues th=
at contributed to the collapse of Silicon Valley Bank and other US regional=
 lenders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI anticipate the need to strengthen c=
apital and liquidity standards=E2=80=9D for banks with assets larger than $=
100 billion, Federal Reserve Vice Chair for Supervision Michael Barr said i=
n answering questions at a Senate Banking Committee hearing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. Chairman Marti=
n Gruenberg said, in his testimony to the panel, that the failures of SVB, =
as Silicon Valley Bank is known, and Signature Bank =E2=80=9Cdemonstrate th=
e implications that banks with assets of $100 billion or more can have for =
financial stability. The prudential regulation of these institutions merits=
 additional attention, particularly with respect to capital, liquidity and =
interest-rate risk.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There will also be some soul-searching about h=
ow SVB was supervised. Here is Barr=E2=80=99s testimony on how the Fed deal=
t with SVB:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Near the end of 2021, supervisors found defici=
encies in the bank=E2=80=99s liquidity risk management, resulting in six su=
pervisory findings related to the bank=E2=80=99s liquidity stress testing, =
contingency funding, and liquidity risk management.=C2=A0In May 2022, super=
visors issued three findings related to ineffective board oversight, risk m=
anagement weaknesses, and the bank=E2=80=99s internal audit function. In th=
e summer of 2022, supervisors lowered the bank=E2=80=99s management rating =
to =E2=80=9Cfair=E2=80=9D and rated the bank=E2=80=99s enterprise-wide gove=
rnance and controls as =E2=80=9Cdeficient-1.=E2=80=9D These ratings mean th=
at the bank was not =E2=80=9Cwell managed=E2=80=9D and was subject to growt=
h restrictions under section 4(m) of the Bank Holding Company Act.=C2=A0In =
October 2022, supervisors met with the bank=E2=80=99s senior management to =
express concern with the bank=E2=80=99s interest rate risk profile and in N=
ovember 2022, supervisors delivered a supervisory finding on interest rate =
risk management to the bank.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In mid-February 2023, staff presented to the F=
ederal Reserve=E2=80=99s Board of Governors on the impact of rising interes=
t rates on some banks=E2=80=99 financial condition and staff=E2=80=99s appr=
oach to address issues at banks. Staff discussed the issues broadly, and hi=
ghlighted SVB=E2=80=99s interest rate and liquidity risk in particular. Sta=
ff relayed that they were actively engaged with SVB but, as it turned out, =
the full extent of the bank=E2=80=99s vulnerability was not apparent until =
the unexpected bank run on March 9. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We need to ask why the bank was unable to fix =
and address the issues we identified in sufficient time. It is not the job =
of supervisors to fix the issues identified; it is the job of the bank=E2=
=80=99s senior management and board of directors to fix its problems.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am reminded of the incredible Credit Suisse =
Group AG <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30986595.=
262435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDct=
MjkvYXJjaGVnb3Mtd2FzLXRvby1idXN5LWZvci1tYXJnaW4tY2FsbHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyODI=
zX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3=
Rlcm09MjMwMzI4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB485=
9ffc0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">  report on how it lost billions of dollars trading with Arc=
hegos Capital Management</a>. Basically Credit Suisse had risk managers and=
 committees who looked at the Archegos exposure, decided it was too big and=
 too undercollateralized, and told the relationship managers to demand more=
 collateral. The relationship managers called Archegos to demand more colla=
teral, and Archegos kept saying =E2=80=9Coh no I=E2=80=99m getting another =
call, gotta take that, will call you back soon.=E2=80=9D Archegos never pos=
ted the collateral, and then it collapsed and took billions of Credit Suiss=
e=E2=80=99s dollars with it. Everyone saw the problem, but nobody acted on =
it with quite enough urgency.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly Esteves is perfectly correct that an=
yone could see SVB=E2=80=99s interest-rate risk, and the Fed did see it. An=
d the Fed=E2=80=99s staff had meetings with the Board of Governors and told=
 them that rising interest rates were going to be rough on a bunch of banks=
, but especially SVB. And the board was like =E2=80=9Chuh so are we doing a=
nything about that,=E2=80=9D and the staff were like =E2=80=9Coh of course =
we=E2=80=99re talking to SVB about managing that risk,=E2=80=9D and in fact=
 they were. Everyone was talking about exactly the right things; they just =
weren=E2=80=99t doing enough about them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also though, when they did, that=E2=80=99s wha=
t broke SVB. Barr again:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank waited too long to address its proble=
ms, and ironically, the overdue actions it finally took to strengthen its b=
alance sheet sparked the uninsured depositor run that led to the bank=E2=80=
=99s failure. Specifically, on Wednesday, March 8, SVB announced that it re=
alized a $1.8 billion loss in a sale of securities to raise liquidity and p=
lanned to raise capital during the following week. Uninsured depositors int=
erpreted these actions as a signal that the bank was in distress. They turn=
ed their focus to the bank=E2=80=99s balance sheet, and they did not like w=
hat they saw.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In response, social media saw a surge in talk =
about a run, and uninsured depositors acted quickly to flee.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you have a bank that is undercapitalized be=
cause it lost money on interest-rate moves, the sensible advice is for it t=
o raise more capital, and that=E2=80=99s what SVB did. But that is also wha=
t blew it up.</p>
