om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">A CDS trade</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A stylized thing that happened in the financia=
l crisis of 2008 is that big international investment banks funded themselv=
es with a lot of very short-term borrowing (repurchase agreements, overnigh=
t loans, derivatives liabilities) from other big market participants (banks=
, hedge funds, etc.), and their lenders hedged their credit risk using cred=
it default swaps. If you had a lot of derivatives exposure to Bear Stearns =
&amp; Co., you might buy some CDS on Bear. If everyone got worried about Be=
ar, (1) they would buy a lot of Bear CDS, pushing its price up and (2) they=
 might stop doing business with Bear or lending it money, causing it to fai=
l. There would be a =E2=80=9Crun on the bank,=E2=80=9D not in the literal s=
ense of depositors lining up to take out their money =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bear wa=
s not an actual bank and didn=E2=80=99t really have depositors =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but in the sense of big short-term lenders declining to roll over their =
loans and terminating derivatives positions. And the CDS market, as an indi=
cator of how big market participants viewed Bear=E2=80=99s credit, was a wa=
rning signal of a potential run. If everyone thinks Bear=E2=80=99s credit i=
s bad, they will not roll their loans.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that was a long time ago and things are di=
fferent now. For one thing, Bear and Lehman Brothers and the other independ=
ent investment banks are gone; these days the big investment banks are most=
ly attached to actual banks that have access to their central banks=E2=80=
=99 lender-of-last-resort facilities. Also those big banks have learned the=
 lessons of 2008 and do not fund themselves with short-term capital-markets=
 borrowing nearly as much as they used to.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Take Deutsche Bank AG, for instance. At the en=
d of 2008, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3098659=
5.262435/aHR0cHM6Ly9pbnZlc3Rvci1yZWxhdGlvbnMuZGIuY29tL2ZpbGVzL2RvY3VtZW50cy=
9hbm51YWwtcmVwb3J0cy9EQl9Bbm51YWxfUmV2aWV3XzIwMDgucGRmP2xhbmd1YWdlX2lkPTE/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc09fc57a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">it reported</a> assets of about =
=E2=82=AC2.2 trillion with just =E2=82=AC32 billion of shareholders=E2=80=
=99 equity.=C2=A0 The rest of its money was borrowed, some in conservative =
bank-y ways (=E2=82=AC396 billion of deposits and=C2=A0=E2=82=AC134 billion=
 of long-term debt), but much of it in riskier capital-markets ways (almost=
 =E2=82=AC1.4 trillion of =E2=80=9Cfinancial liabilities at fair value thro=
ugh profit or loss,=E2=80=9D including derivatives liabilities, plus =E2=80=
=9Cother short-term borrowings=E2=80=9D). At the end of 2022, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30986595.262435/aHR0cHM6Ly9pbnZ=
lc3Rvci1yZWxhdGlvbnMuZGIuY29tL2ZpbGVzL2RvY3VtZW50cy9hbm51YWwtcmVwb3J0cy8yMD=
IzL0FubnVhbC1SZXBvcnQtMjAyMi5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb178cc55" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">it reported</a> assets of about=C2=A0=E2=82=AC1.3 trillion and equity of=
=C2=A0=E2=82=AC72 billion, more than doubling its equity while almost halvi=
ng its assets. Meanwhile much more of its funding comes from deposits (=E2=
=82=AC621 billion, along with=C2=A0=E2=82=AC132 billion of long-term debt) =
and much less comes from short-term capital-markets-y stuff (=E2=82=AC388 b=
illion of fair-value liabilities and just=C2=A0=E2=82=AC5 billion of other =
short-term borrowings). Deposits went from about 18% of its funding to abou=
t 46%. If there was going to be a run on the bank at Deutsche Bank in 2008,=
 it would have been Deutsche=E2=80=99s derivatives counterparties getting n=
ervous. If there was going to be a run on the bank at Deutsche Bank in 2023=
, it would have been a regular run on the regular bank, with depositors get=
ting nervous and taking their money out.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile the market for single-name credit de=
fault swaps is also <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/30986595.262435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmV3eW9ya2ZlZC5vcmcvbWVkaWFsaWJyYXJ5L21lZ=
GlhL3Jlc2VhcmNoL2Vwci8yMDIwL2Vwcl8yMDIwX3ZvbDI2bm8zLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a=
