 all but collapsed now that UBS Group AG has agreed to buy its beleaguered =
rival. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">UBS executives will be less inclined to take K=
lein=E2=80=99s advice. They=E2=80=99re still trying to untangle his deal, a=
ccording to people familiar with the matter. Rather than spinning out the i=
nvestment bank, UBS is planning to cherry pick the best people to bring ove=
r.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Apparently Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s agreement t=
o buy Klein=E2=80=99s boutique still exists, and Klein =E2=80=9Ccould walk =
away with more than a $20 million break-up fee,=E2=80=9D along with his $10=
 million retainer. It would be funny if he sued for specific performance, b=
ut don=E2=80=99t count on it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is one good irony here, which is that Kl=
ein apparently gets credit for bringing Saudi investors into Credit Suisse=
=E2=80=99s stock:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He encouraged longtime clients in =
Saudi Arabia to invest $1.5 billion in Credit Suisse only to have the bank =
collapse into the arms of a competitor shortly after. They lost more than $=
1 billion of their money. He was lining up even more capital from the Middl=
e East and the private equity industry for CS First Boston.</p></blockquote=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why did Credit Suisse collapse? The simple ver=
sion of the story is that the chairman of the Saudi National Bank, Credit S=
uisse=E2=80=99s largest shareholder, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30986595.262435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdz=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjcvc2F1ZGktbmF0aW9uYWwtYmFuay1jaGFpcm1hbi1yZXNpZ25=
zLWFmdGVyLWNyZWRpdC1zdWlzc2UtY29tbWVudD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzI4MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRi=
Z1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjgmd=
XRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8da80bac" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 went on Bloomberg TV a few weeks ago and said</a> the bank would =E2=80=9C=
absolutely not=E2=80=9D put any more money into Credit Suisse. And then the=
 stock dropped, depositors fled, and Credit Suisse vanished in short order.=
 Just an incredible unforced error! I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/30986595.262435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTUvc2lsaWNvbi12YWxsZXktYmFuay1pcy1mb3Itc2FsZT=
9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzI4MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9b=
mV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cD41c0a024" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote at the time</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look I suppose that if you are the=
 biggest shareholder of a somewhat beleaguered bank and someone asks you on=
 television =E2=80=9Cwould you throw more money into this bank,=E2=80=9D an=
d the actual answer is =E2=80=9Cno we can=E2=80=99t,=E2=80=9D you should no=
t say =E2=80=9Cyes.=E2=80=9D Everything is securities fraud, etc. But =E2=
=80=A6 you should not =E2=80=A6 say =E2=80=9Cno=E2=80=9D? You certainly sho=
uld not say =E2=80=9Cabsolutely not=E2=80=9D? =E2=80=9CWe believe strongly =
in Credit Suisse, we are in close contact with management, and we ourselves=
 have access to tons of cash=E2=80=9D: Nothing in that sentence is a lie, i=
t does not actually answer the question, and yet it sounds like it does? It=
 sounds vaguely confidence-inspiring? I thought of that in three seconds? Y=
ou could probably do better if it was your money on the line?</p></blockquo=
te>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose no one could have predicted those te=
levision comments =E2=80=94=C2=A0they were really so unnecessary! =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but what if you could have? What if Klein had come to Credit Suisse a=
nd said =E2=80=9Clook I have lined up some big Saudi investors who will put=
 in $1.5 billion to shore up our capital position, but they might say some =
bad stuff about us on television=E2=80=9D? Knowing that in advance, would y=
ou take the deal? I think Credit Suisse would clearly have been better off =
without the $1.5 billion and the stray comments on TV.</p>
