<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a business logic to owning a professi=
onal sports team. You spend money on players and facilities and expertise, =
which makes your team good. Because your team is good, people watch it, and=
 its revenue goes up, so the money you spent pays off and you make a profit=
 on your investment.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is also a luxury-consumption logic to ow=
ning a professional sports team. You spend money on players etc., which mak=
es your team good. Because your team is good, you have fun, because it is f=
un to root for a winning sports team and I suppose it is even more fun if y=
ou own the team. You get to, like, go to the clubhouse and high-five the pl=
ayers after a win, or you get to turn on the radio and listen to a sports t=
alk show and hear people say =E2=80=9Chey that=C2=A0owner they got is prett=
y good.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot of modern sports owners (1) are rich, (2=
) are sports fans and (3)=C2=A0got their money by building profitable busin=
esses. There is a tension between running their team like a business and ru=
nning it for fun. They are after all mostly businesspeople, and sports team=
s are expensive, so they have a natural inclination to run it like a busine=
ss and earn a return. On the other hand there are probably better businesse=
s, and they got into this one for fun, so it seems a shame not to have fun.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If every owner feels this tension in roughly t=
he same degree, then you have a nice competitive dynamic: Everyone spends t=
o try to win, and they all spend about the same amount, so the league is co=
mpetitive.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if you had an owner who (1) was very very =
rich and (2) did not care at all about running it like a business, that own=
er would have a lot of fun indeed.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Other owners =E2=80=94 ones who were less rich and more inclined =
to seek a return on their investment =E2=80=94=C2=A0would have much less fu=
n: The free-spending fun-loving owner would win too many games, which would=
 reduce the other owners=E2=80=99 <em>sporting=C2=A0</em>enjoyment (they do=
 care about winning!) but also their revenues (their fans also care about w=
inning). So most big modern sports leagues are set up to restrict the abili=
ty of an owner to spend too much money: US leagues tend to have salary caps=
 so rich owners can=E2=80=99t spend too much on players; European soccer ha=
s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30986595.262435/=
aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvVUVGQV9GaW5hbmNpYWxfRmFpcl9QbGF5X1J=
lZ3VsYXRpb25z/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe516333f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> =E2=80=9Cfinancia=
l fair play=E2=80=9D rules</a>=C2=A0so rich owners can=E2=80=99t spend more=
 than their clubs earn.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30986595.262435/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMy8wMy8y=
Ni9zcG9ydHMvYmFzZWJhbGwvc3RldmUtY29oZW4tbWV0cy1uZXcteW9yay5odG1s/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB21bc86de" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the New York Times has a story about Stev=
e Cohen</a> and his ownership of the=C2=A0New York Mets, the gist of which =
is that Cohen can spend as much as he wants on making the Mets good, so he =
is, and it=E2=80=99s working, and he=E2=80=99s having a lot of fun and New =
York sports talk radio loves him for it:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He is at once an extreme version of a type =E2=
=80=94 the munificent steward, willing to lose money in a show of how much =
money he=E2=80=99s made =E2=80=94 and a model all his own, his tenure rocke=
ting toward something that can feel like a referendum for the man, the Mets=
, their city and the sport itself.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Cohen, 66, has carried off a remarkable revers=
al in public standing, migrating over the past decade from a reclusive avat=
ar of scofflaw capitalism to an avuncular Twitterer who could probably be e=
lected Queens borough president by acclamation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Mets have swiftly shed their ingrained ide=
ntity as lovable losers, their ownership shifting from the cost-conscious, =
Madoff-swindled Wilpon family to a white-collar boundary-pusher long apprai=
sed as neither lovable nor a loser. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And baseball is grappling with the ramificatio=
ns of Cohen=E2=80=99s runaway spending in the nation=E2=80=99s most capital=
istic major league, where no salary cap constrains him and only one team th=
ought to buy Super Bowl ad time just because it could. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CKeep spending,=E2=80=9D Joe Kessler, =
61, a retiree from Bayside, Queens, told Cohen in January at a community ev=
ent at Citi Field, where the Mets were finishing construction on the league=
=E2=80=99s largest scoreboard.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf I spend any more,=E2=80=9D Cohen r=
eplied, according to Kessler, nodding at rival owners=E2=80=99 frustrations=
, =E2=80=9Cthey=E2=80=99ll find me rubbed out somewhere.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I love that, in the absence of a salary cap or=
 financial-fair-play rules, the way that baseball constrains one owner=E2=
=80=99s excessive spending is with a vague implicit threat of murder. Anywa=
y I don=E2=80=99t understand why more people don=E2=80=99t do this! If you =
have made a large fortune, and if a lot of people think that it is sort of =
ill-gotten, you will be tempted to launder your reputation by sponsoring a =
wing at the art museum or a new building for a symphony, but it seems clear=
ly better to buy a lovable-loser baseball team and plow enormous amounts of=
 money into making it good. Who could object to that?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also here is this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And when Cohen=E2=80=99s young son seemed prim=
ed for batting lessons many years back, the family hired Art Shamsky, from =
the 1969 World Series champions, for private sessions in Central Park, wher=
e Shamsky hauled a hitting tee that often felt decorative.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CHe just wanted to run after squirrels=
,=E2=80=9D Shamsky said of the boy, who now works in cryptocurrency.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just a devastating sentence.</p>
